    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-09-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-09-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="240"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d240">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/1051.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador to Great Britain</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 11, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Peking telegraphs as follows:</p>
                <p>[Telegram September 11 from the American Minister.]</p>
                <p>You will mention this report at the Foreign Office and discuss it in connection
                    with the reported German loan (see Department’s September 11 to Berlin). The
                    Department has no doubt however that the British Government will uniformly deter
                    its nationals from any loan to China inconsistent with the policy as to which
                    our two Governments are in accord.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
